/*!
    \page mkspecs-reference.html
    \title Reference
    \previouspage Metadata Generation
    \nextpage Variables

    
    The reference sections describes in detail additonnal variables and functions that are available 
    for use in qmake project files.

    
    \section1 Variable Reference

    \l {Variables} describes the additonnal variables that are recognized by qmake when configuring 
    the build process for projects.

    \l {Pseudo Variables} describes the variables that are evaluated late in project build process. 
    In contrary to standard variables, they only use a single dollar-sign and their contents is not 
    available during project file processing.
    
    \note Pseudo variables requires \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)} or later, except if used in:
        \list
            \li output variables: \c {DESTDIR}, \c {DLLDESTDIR}, \l {INSTALLDIR}.
            \li include variables: \l {IQUOTEPATH}, \c {INCLUDEPATH}.
            \li dependencies variables: \c {LIBS}, \l {PLUGINS}, \c {PRE_TARGETDEPS}, 
                \c {POST_TARGETDEPS}.
            \li installation variables (i.e. \c {INSTALLS} sub-variables).
        \endlist
    
    
    \section1 Function Reference

    These functions are divided into categories according to their type:

    \list
        \li \l {Replace Functions}
        \li \l {Test Functions}
    \endlist
*/


/*!
    \page mkspecs-variable-reference.html
    \title Variables
    \previouspage Reference
    \nextpage Pseudo Variables

    
    \section1 BOOST
    
    Specifies a list of Boost modules that are linked to this target. An additional variable member 
    is available to define the type of dependency:

    \table
    \header
        \li Member
        \li {2, 1} Value
    \row
        \li {1, 3} \c {CONFIG}
        \li \c {shared} 
        \li \b {\e {by default:}} modules are linked dynamically to this target (ignored for static 
            library project).
    \row
        \li \c {static}
        \li modules are linked statically to this target (ignored for static library project).
    \row
        \li \c {combined}
        \li modules are combined to this target in case of static library project; otherwise is 
            same as \c {static} value.
    \endtable
    
    For example:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  BOOST reference
    
    See also \l {Boost Support}.
    
    
    \section1 BOOST_ROOT
    
    Contains the path to the Boost root directory. This variable is empty if:

    \list
        \li \c {BOOST_ROOT} environment variable is not defined.
        \li Boost feature is not supported by current platform and build environment.
    \endlist

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.

    
    \section1 BOOST_INCLUDEDIR

    Contains the path to the directory containing Boost's headers. This variable is empty if
    \l {BOOST_ROOT} is not defined.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
    
    
    \section1 BOOST_LIBRARYDIR

    Contains the path to the directory containing separately-compiled Boost libraries. This 
    variable is empty if \l {BOOST_ROOT} is not defined.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
    
    
    \section1 BOOST_VERSION

    Contains the current version of Boost. This variable is empty if Boost version cannot be 
    resolved.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
    
    
    \section1 IQUOTEPATH

    Specifies the headers directory paths to the list of directories to be searched for header files, 
    only for the case of \c {#include "file"}. To lookup for \c {#include <file>} directives, use 
    \c {INCLUDEPATH} variable instead. 
    
    For example:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  IQUOTEPATH reference
    
    Specific quoted headers search paths is currently only supported by GCC compilers. For Visual 
    C++ compiler, directories is append to \c {INCLUDEPATH} variable.
    

    \section1 INSTALLDIR
    
    Specifies the directory where project files will be installed.

    See also \l {Installation Definition}.
    

    \section1 LIBRARYPATH
    
    Specifies the directories where archiver or linker will search for archives and shared libraries 
    to link into the project.
    
    For example:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  LIBRARYPATH reference


    \section1 LITERAL_QUOTES

    Useless from \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)}. This variable is used whenever a literal double quote 
    (\c {"}) is needed in a variable declaration, and which would not be interpreted as such by 
    qmake parser.

    
    \section1 LITERAL_OPEN_BRACE

    Useless from \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)}. This variable is used whenever a literal open brace 
    (\tt {\unicode {0x7B}}) is needed in a variable declaration, and which would not be interpreted 
    as such by qmake parser.
    

    \section1 LITERAL_CLOSE_BRACE
    
    Useless from \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)}. This variable is used whenever a literal close brace 
    (\tt {\unicode {0x7D}}) is needed in a variable declaration, and which would not be interpreted 
    as such by qmake parser.
    

    \section1 PLUGINS
    
    Specifies a list of shared libraries path that are not linked into the project but may be loaded 
    dynamically at runtime. Note that each library must be passed with its full path.

    For example:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  PLUGINS reference
    
    The list of libraries stored in \c {PLUGINS} is reduced to a list of unique names.
    
    
    \section1 PROPERTIES
    
    Specifies target informations to be passed to the application if the app template is specified, 
    or the library if the lib template is specified. The allowed values are:
    
    \table
    \header
        \li Member
        \li Description
    \row
        \li \c {name}
        \li The display name of application / library. Defaults to \c {TARGET} if empty.
    \row
        \li \c {version}
        \li The target version number. Defaults to \c {unversioned} if empty or invalid. \br
            \c {VERSION}, \c {VER_MAJ}, \c {VER_MIN} and \c {VER_PAT} variables are overridden 
            by this version number, or reset to \c {0} if property is equals to \c {unversioned}.
    \row
        \li \c {product}
        \li The product name for the project target. Defaults to \c {TARGET} if empty. \br
            \e {Windows only:} \c {QMAKE_TARGET_PRODUCT} variable is overridden by this property.
    \row
        \li \c {description}
        \li The target description. \br
            \e {Windows only:} \c {QMAKE_TARGET_DESCRIPTION} variable is overridden by this property.
    \row
        \li \c {company}
        \li The name of the organization (i.e. company or author) publishing the project target. \br
            \e {Windows only:} \c {QMAKE_TARGET_COMPANY} variable is overridden by this property.
    \row
        \li \c {domain}
        \li The internet domain for the organization (taken into account if \c {company} property 
            is set).
    \row
        \li \c {year}
        \li The target publication year. Defaults to current year if empty.
    \row
        \li \c {copyright}
        \li The copyright information for the project target. This variable allows \c {%c} and 
            \c {%y} modifiers respectively replaced with company and year properties. \br
            \e {Windows only:} \c {QMAKE_TARGET_COPYRIGHT} variable is overridden by this property.
    \endtable
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  PROPERTIES reference

    \note Windows resource file generation requires \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)} or later. Previous 
    versions use \b {verpatch} tool to update target version and properties.
    
    Moreover, qmake generates \c {info_$${TARGET}.h} and \c {info_$${TARGET}.cpp} source files in 
    intermediate directory \tt {generated/$${\l {TOOLKIT}.mkspec}/${LIBRARY_MODE}/${BUILD_MODE}/info}, 
    in order to:
    
    \list
        \li access to these properies in the application or library source code.
        \li initialize following \c {QCoreApplication} properties in case of case of Qt application.
    \endlist
    
    \table
    \header
        \li Property
        \li Initialized with
    \row
        \li \c {applicationName}
        \li \c {PROPERTIES.name}
    \row
        \li \c {applicationVersion}
        \li \c {PROPERTIES.version}
    \row
        \li \c {organizationDomain}
        \li \c {PROPERTIES.domain}
    \row
        \li \c {organizationName}
        \li \c {PROPERTIES.company}
    \endtable

    Below the source code of \c {info_$${TARGET}.h} generated by qmake:
    
    \code
        #ifndef INFO_{TARGETNAME}_H
        #define INFO_{TARGETNAME}_H

        namespace {TargetName} {
                        
            const char * name();            // returns PROPERTIES.name value
            const char * version();         // returns PROPERTIES.version value
            const char * product();         // returns PROPERTIES.product value
            const char * organization();    // returns PROPERTIES.company value
            const char * copyright();       // returns PROPERTIES.copyright value
                        
        }

        #endif
    \endcode
    
    \e {Before Qt 5.1:} additional function \c {void setup( QCoreApplication * )} is provided to 
    initialize \c {QCoreApplication} properties, since automatic initialization on application 
    startup is not supported.

    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_APP
    
    Contains the default extension used on applications.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.

    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_ICO
    
    Windows only. Contains the extension used on icon files.

            
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_IMPLIB
    
    Windows only. Contains the default extension used on import libraries.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
    
    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_QML
    
    Contains suffixes for files which should be interpreted as QML files.
    
    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_QRC
    
    Contains the extension used on Qt resource collection files.
    
    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_SHLIB
    
    Contains the default extension used on shared libraries.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.


    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_STATICLIB
    
    Contains the default extension used on static libraries.

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
    
    
    \section1 QMAKE_EXT_TS
    
    Contains the extension used on Qt Linguist translation files.
    
    
    \section1 QMAKE_METADATA_GENERATORS
    
    Specifies a list of additional metadata generators.
    
    See also \l {Metadata Generation}.


    \section1 QML_FILES
    
    Specifies the names of all QML files in the project.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  QML_FILES reference
    
    \note QML files registration requires \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)} or later.
    
    
    \section1 QSMAKEPATH

    Contains the path to the root directory containing the QS qmake features. Note that features 
    files reside within a mkspecs sub-directory (i.e. \c {$${QMAKEPATH}/mkspecs/<features>}), as 
    required by Qt framework.

    For example, the following line causes the location of the directory containing the QS qmake 
    features to be written to the console:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  QSMAKEPATH reference

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.


    \section1 TOOLKIT

    Provides information about platform and build environment taken into account to generate the 
    project target:

    \table
    \header
        \li Member
        \li Value
    \row
        \li \c {host.platform}
        \li Plaftorm name (\c {win}, \c {linux}...).
    \row
        \li \c {host.arch}
        \li Plaftorm architecture (\c {x86}, \c {x64}...).
    \row
        \li \c {compiler.name}
        \li Compiler name (\c {msvc}, \c {gcc}...).
    \row
        \li \c {compiler.version}
        \li Compiler version.
    \row
        \li \c {compiler}
        \li Compiler identifier: \c {$${TOOLKIT.compiler.name}$${TOOLKIT.compiler.version}}.
    \row
        \li \c {mkspec}
        \li Toolkit mkspec shortname: \c {$${TOOLKIT.host.platform}-$${TOOLKIT.compiler}-$${TOOLKIT.host.arch}}.
    \endtable
        
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  TOOLKIT reference
        
    Note that any \c {TOOLKIT} property may be queried from a qmake command line, by passing the 
    \c {QUERY_TOOLKIT_PROPERTY=}\a {property} argument. For example, the following command line 
    returns the \c {TOOLKIT.mkpsec} value used in the current project:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  QUERY_TOOLKIT_PROPERTY reference
    
    \note Do not attempt to overwrite properties values of this variable.

    
    \section1 _PRO_FILE_NAME_

    Contains the base name of the project file in use, without extension.

    For example, the following line causes the base name of the project file to be written to the 
    console:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  _PRO_FILE_NAME_ reference

    \note Do not attempt to overwrite the value of this variable.
*/


/*!
    \page mkspecs-pseudo-variable-reference.html
    \title Pseudo Variables
    \previouspage Variables
    \nextpage Replace Functions

    
    \section1 BUILD_MODE

    Contains the mode in which the target is being built. If \c {debug_and_release} option is 
    enabled, this variable is empty during meta-target generation pass.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  BUILD_MODE reference
    
    
    \section1 LIBRARY_MODE

    Library target only. If \c {static_and_shared} option is enabled, contains the type of library 
    taken into account when the target is being built. This variable is empty during meta-target 
    generation pass.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  LIBRARY_MODE reference
*/


/*!
    \page mkspecs-replace-function-reference.html
    \title Replace Functions
    \previouspage Pseudo Variables
    \nextpage Test Functions
    
    
    \section1 append(variablename, suffix)
    
    Appends each value stored in \a {variablename} with \a {suffix}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  append() reference
    
    See also \l {prepend(variablename, prefix)}{prepend()}.


    \section1 prepend(variablename, prefix)
    
    Prepends each value stored in \a {variablename} with \a {prefix}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  prepend() reference
    
    See also \l {append(variablename, suffix)}{append()}.


    \section1 remove(variablename, substr)
    
    Removes each instance that matches the regular expression \a {substr} in the contents of 
    \a {variablename}.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  remove() reference

    
    \section1 TARGET([mode])
    
    Returns the contents of \c {TARGET} according to the current build \a {mode}. If \c {TARGET} 
    does not contain any debug modifier, this function returns the same value regardless of the 
    given \a {mode}.
    
    \a {mode} can have one of the following values: \c {debug} or \c {release} (fallback value if 
    argument is not specified or invalid).

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  TARGET() reference
    
    See also \l {Target Definition}.
*/


/*!
    \page mkspecs-test-function-reference.html
    \title Test Functions
    \previouspage Replace Functions
    
    
    \section1 add_subdir(target, path[, depends])
    
    Subdirs-based project only. Specifies a subdirectory \a {target}, located in \a {path}, that 
    will be registered as part of the projects group. \a {path} argument may:
    
    \list
        \li be empty. In this case \a {target} value will be used as subdirectory path.
        \li point to a subdirectory. In this case subproject \c {.pro} file should have the same 
            base name as the subdirectory itself.
        \li point to a subproject \c {.pro} file.
    \endlist
        
    Optional subdirectories targets may be passed in \a {depends} argument to define subproject 
    build start constraints. Note that to ensure subdirs dependencies resolution, \a {target} should 
    have the same name as subproject's \c {TARGET} '\c {release}' value.
    
        
    \section1 add_library(type, path, targets)

    Binary target only. Specifies library \a {targets}, located in \a {path}, to use when linking to 
    / archiving the current target. \a {type} should be given to specify the type of dependency:
    
    \list
        \li \c {static} defines static libraries linked to this target (ignored for static library 
            project).
        \li \c {shared} defines shared libraries linked to this target (ignored for static library 
            project).
        \li \c {combined} defines static libraries combined to this target in case of static library 
            project; otherwise is same as \c {static} value.
    \endlist
    
    Any library in \a {targets} can be defined either by library name (without extension and 
    optional platform dependent prefix), or by file name. Optional \c {[.ext]} modifier can also be 
    used in \a {targets} values in order to append system-default library extension.
    
    If \a {path} is set to \c {system} value, this function registers the given system libraries as 
    target dependencies. Note that \c {system} path is not supported for \c {combined} dependencies 
    on static library project. Furthermore, any pseudo variable \tt {${\l {LIBRARY_MODE}}} occurrence 
    defined in \a {path} argument will be substituted by \a {type} argument value.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  add_library() reference
    
    See also \l {Target Dependencies}.
    

    \section1 add_plugin(path, targets)
    
    Binary target only. Specifies plugin \a {targets}, located in \a {path}, dynamically loadable by 
    the current target. Any library in \a {targets} can be defined either by library name (without 
    extension and optional platform dependent prefix), or by file name. Optional \c {[.ext]} 
    modifier can also be used in \a {targets} values in order to append system-default library 
    extension.
    
    Any pseudo variable \tt {${\l {LIBRARY_MODE}}} occurrence defined in \a {path} argument will be 
    substituted by \c {shared} value.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  add_plugin() reference
    
    See also \l {Target Dependencies}.

    
    \section1 assert(condition)

    Evaluates given \a {condition}. If the condition is \c {false}, qmake aborts this project (and 
    its \c {SUBDIRS}) processing.

    For example, processing of the project below will stop if \c {SOURCES} variable is empty:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  assert() reference
    
    
    \section1 build_mode(mode)
    
    Succeeds if the target is being built in the specified \a {mode}; otherwise fails. \a {mode} can 
    have one of the following values: \c {debug} or \c {release}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  build_mode() reference
    
    See also \l {build_pass([types])} {build_pass()}.
    

    \section1 build_pass([types])

    Succeeds if the target is being built; otherwise fails. If \a {types} is specified, this 
    function also checks the type of target currently processed. See \l {TEMPLATE(types)} {TEMPLATE()} 
    for more details about \a {types} argument.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  build_pass() reference
    
    This function never fails if \a {types} is not specified and if \c {debug_and_release} / 
    \c {static_and_shared} options are disabled.


    \section1 endsWith(variablename, value)

    Tests whether \a {variablename} ends with a value that matches the regular expression \a {value}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  endsWith() reference

    See also \l {startsWith(variablename, value)} {startsWith()}.
    

    \section1 find(variablename, substr)

    Tests whether at least one of the values in \a {variablename} matches the regular expression 
    \a {substr}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  find() reference
    
    
    \section1 glob(variablename, patterns[, base])

    Expands the specified wildcard \a {patterns}, and adds the resolved list of filenames in 
    \a {variablename}. If \a {base} is specified, filenames added will be relative to the given 
    \a {base} path.
    
    See also \l {rglob(variablename, patterns[, base])} {rglob()}.
    

    \section1 is_absolute_path(path)

    Succeeds if \a {path} is an absolute path; otherwise fails if it is relative.
    
    
    \section1 isNull(variablename)
    
    Succeeds if the variable \a {variablename} is defined (even if it is empty); otherwise fails.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  isNull() reference

    \note This function requires \b {qmake 3.0 (Qt 5.0)} or later.
    
    
    \section1 is_relative_path(path)

    Succeeds if \a {path} is a relative path; otherwise fails if it is absolute.

        
    \section1 qsdeprecated(string)

    Displays \a {string} as a deprecation message to the user. Message is prefixed by the processed 
    project name.

    
    \section1 qserror(string)

    Displays \a {string} as an error message to the user and exits. Message is prefixed by the 
    processed project name.
    

    \section1 qsmessage(string)

    Displays \a {string} as a general message to the user. Message is prefixed by the processed 
    project name.


    \section1 qswarning(string)
    
    Displays \a {string} as a warning message to the user. Message is prefixed by the processed 
    project name.
    

    \section1 QT(modules)
    
    Succeeds if the \c {QT} variable contains the specied \a {modules}; otherwise fails. It is 
    possible to specify a regular expression for \a {modules} parameter.
    
    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  QT() reference
    
    
    \section1 qtGreaterThan(version[, equals])

    Tests that the current Qt version is greater than value \a {version}, or equals if \a {equals} 
    argument is set to \c {true}. Version argument expects a \c {major.minor[.patch]} format to be 
    taken into account.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  qtGreaterThan() reference

    See also \l {qtLessThan(version[, equals])}{qtLessThan()}.
    
    
    \section1 qtLessThan(version[, equals])

    Tests that the current Qt version is smaller than value \a {version}, or equals if \a {equals} 
    argument is set to \c {true}. Works as \l {qtGreaterThan(version[, equals])} {qtGreaterThan()}
    function.
    
    
    \section1 rglob(variablename, patterns[, base])

    Expands the specified wildcard \a {patterns} recursively into subdirectories, and adds the 
    resolved list of filenames in \a {variablename}. If \a {base} is specified, filenames added will 
    be relative to the given \a {base} path.

    See also \l {glob(variablename, patterns[, base])} {glob()}.
    
    
    \section1 startsWith(variablename, value)

    Tests whether \a {variablename} starts with a value that matches the regular expression 
    \a {value}.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  startsWith() reference
    
    See also \l {endsWith(variablename, value)} {endsWith()}.
    
    
    \section1 TEMPLATE(types)
    
    Tests whether the type of target currently processed matches one of the specified \a {types}:

    \list
        \li \c {aux} defines an auxiliary project.
        \li \c {subdirs} defines a subdirs-based project.
        \li \c {app} defines an application target.
        \li \c {static} defines a static library target.
        \li \c {shared} defines a shared library target.
        \li \c {lib} defines a static or shared library target.
        \li \c {plugin} defines a static or shared plugin target.
        \li \c {pseudo} defines a non-build artifact project (auxiliary or subdirs-based).
        \li \c {binary} defines a binary file project (application or library).
    \endlist
    
    \a {types} argument supports a set of types separated by \c {|} character.

    For example:
    
    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  TEMPLATE() reference

    Note that above \c {TEMPLATE} values may be queried from a qmake command line, by passing the 
    \c {QUERY_TARGET_PROPERTY=template} argument. For example, the following command line returns 
    the type of target defined in the current project:

    \snippet doc_src_mkspecs-manual.pro  QUERY_TAMPLATE_PROPERTY reference
*/
